[1] WHO sitrep 3 Dec 2014
Date: 3 Dec 2014
Source: WHO [edited]
http://who.int/csr/disease/ebola/situation-reports/en


Situation summary
Latest available situation summary, 3 Dec 2014
---------------------------------------
HIGHLIGHTS
There have been 17 145 reported cases of Ebola virus disease (EVD), with 6070 reported deaths.
- Case incidence is slightly increasing in Guinea, stable or declining in Liberia, and may still be increasing in Sierra Leone.
- The outbreak in Spain has been declared over.
- The UNMEER [UN Mission for Ebola Emergency Response] targets of isolating and treating 70 percent of EVD cases and burying 70 percent of EVD-related deaths safely have likely been met in most districts of Guinea, Liberia, and Sierra Leone. All 3 countries now have sufficient capacity at a national level to meet both targets, though local variations mean capacity is still insufficient to stop transmission in some areas.

SUMMARY
A total of 17 145 confirmed, probable, and suspected cases of Ebola virus disease (EVD) have been reported in 5 affected countries (Guinea, Liberia, Mali, Sierra Leone, and the United States of America) and 3 previously affected countries (Nigeria, Senegal and Spain) up to the end of 30 November. There have been 6070 reported deaths.

Reported case incidence is slightly increasing in Guinea (77 confirmed cases reported in the week to 30 Nov 2014), stable or declining in Liberia (43 new confirmed cases in the 5 days to 28 Nov 2014), and is still rising in Sierra Leone (537 new confirmed cases in the week to 30 Nov 2014). The case fatality rate across the 3 most affected countries in all cases with a recorded definitive outcome is 72 percent; in hospitalized patients the case fatality rate is 60 percent.

Response activities in the 3 intense-transmission countries continue to intensify in line with the UNMEER aim to isolate and treat 70 percent of EVD cases and safely bury 70 percent of EVD-related deaths by 1 Dec 2014, with the ultimate goal of reaching 100 percent by 1 Jan 2015.

Beds
------
At a national level, there is now sufficient bed capacity in EVD treatment facilities to treat and isolate all reported EVD cases in each of the 3 countries, although the uneven distribution of beds and cases means there are serious shortfalls in some areas.

Burials
---------
Similarly, each country now has sufficient and widespread capacity to bury all reported EVD-related deaths; however, because not all EVD-related deaths are reported, and many reported burials are of non-EVD-related deaths, it is possible that the 70 percent target has not been met in some areas.

Laboratory confirmation
---------------------
Every EVD-affected district in the 3 intense-transmission countries has access to a laboratory for confirmation within 24 hours of sample collection.

Contacts
------
All 3 countries report that more than 85 percent of registered contacts associated with known cases of EVD are being traced, although contact tracing is still a challenge in areas of intense transmission. Increasing capacity for contact tracing in areas with low levels of transmission will be necessary to end local chains of transmission.

[Tables showing key performance indicators for the Ebola response in the 3 countries, maps and a section: "3. Preparedness Of [African] Countries To Rapidly Detect And Respond To An Ebola Exposure" may be seen at the Source link].

