[4] World Bank update shows worsening economic impact
Date: Tue 2 Dec 2014
Source: CIDRAP [edited]
http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2014/12/msf-pushes-more-agile-hands-approach-ebola-battle


The World Bank Group today [2 Dec 2014] released new estimates of the financial impact of the Ebola outbreak on Guinea, Liberia, and Sierra Leone, showing further dips in gross domestic product (GDP) for this year [2014] and projections for negative growth in 2015 for Guinea and Sierra Leone.

The Tue 2 Dec 2014 report updates the World Bank's 8 Oct 2014 analysis and comes as World Bank President Jim Young Kim starts a 2-day visit to West Africa to gauge the financial fallout from the epidemic and talk to governments and aid groups about response needs. The group has mobilized USD 1 billion for the 3 countries.

Though all 3 countries had been growing rapidly in recent years, including the 1st half of 2014 in the outbreak's early months, the World Bank sharply revised the GDP growth estimates downward in October 2014 and predicted further drops in its new report. For 2015, the group projects negative growth of -0.2 percent for Guinea and -2.0 percent for Sierra Leone. For Liberia, where signs of progress against the outbreak have been seen, along with some increasing economic activity, the World Bank projects a 3 percent increase, up from its 1 percent projection in October [2014] but less than half of the pre-crisis estimate of 6.8 percent.

The group put the income loss for 2014 and 2015 for all 3 countries at more than USD 2 billion. Kim said in the statement: "This report reinforces why zero Ebola cases must be our goal. While there are signs of progress, as long as the epidemic continues, the human and economic impact will only grow more devastating."... - more

[Byline: Lisa Schnirring]

